    <text id="A8051T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Lushbaugh tries to clarify finances with McCue, and McCue's attempt to pay debt
                    with "potatoes."</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    Harman Lushbaugh<lb/><hi rend="underline">1860</hi>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1860-01-21">Jan. 21st 1860</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>J. H. McCue <abbr expan="Esquire">Esq</abbr><lb/>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>The day I received your letter I saw Mr Speck who had received one also. And it
                    was the first time that I ever had heard any thing in regard to the potatoes. he
                    (Mr. Speck) says he never agreed to to take them as pay for what you owed him he
                    said it would not suit him. I never bought them from him as your little Son
                    supposes, But very late in the fall I concluded to have them dug thinking that
                    you intended me to have them as no one came to get them I also measured them to
                    see how many they were so when I seen you if you did not intend me to have them
                    I would pay<pb n="2"/>you for them.</p>
                <p>There was six bushels and a half, you can write to me and let me know who I shall
                    pay for them</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>yours with much<lb/>respect</salute>
                    <signed>H J Lushbaugh</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
